	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Volatility in the Guyanese poultry sector</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 November 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the Government of Guyana’s ‘Commodity market update’ of June 2011, poultry meat production in Guyana ‘in the first quarter of 2011 increased 27.8% when compared to the levels of output in the first quarter of 2010’. However production decreased in the second quarter by 9.95%, leaving overall production up only 8.98% in the first six months of 2011 compared to 2010.</p><p>A shortage of chicken emerged on the local market, with prices for consumers increasing markedly. This followed a shortfall in the expected output of one of the big hatcheries, and cutbacks in production in response to ‘a major surplus of chicken earlier in the year’. This led the government in August 2011 to issue local poultry producers with ‘short-term licences to import chicken’. This is expected to be a short-term measure, as national supplies of chicken are expected to return to normal by mid September 2011.</p><p>The Caribbean Poultry Association warned however that the industry ‘is faced once again with the reality that global prices of feed ingredients and other inputs have been increasing significantly when compared to last year’s prices’. This, it is maintained, is ‘affecting the poultry industry worldwide’ since it has ‘a negative impact on the price of chicken’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Guyana, Ministry of Agriculture, ‘Commodity market update’, June 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.agriculture.gov.gy/Commodities%20Update/CMU%20Q2%202011.pdf" target="_self">http://www.agriculture.gov.gy/Commodities%20Update/CMU%20Q2%202011.pdf</a></p><p><i>Thepoultrysite.com</i>, ‘Poultry imports allowed’, 18 August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thepoultrysite.com/poultrynews/23374/poultry-imports-allowed" target="_self">http://www.thepoultrysite.com/poultrynews/23374/poultry-imports-allowed</a></p><p><i>Thepoultrysite.com</i>, ‘Domestic chicken supply stabilised’, 11 August 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thepoultrysite.com/poultrynews/23319/domestic-chicken-supply-stabilised" target="_self">http://www.thepoultrysite.com/poultrynews/23319/domestic-chicken-supply-...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The volatility in the Guyana poultry sector would appear to highlight the importance of securing long-term sources of poultry feed at competitive and stable prices. In the second quarter of 2011, high feed prices appear to have acted as a disincentive to poultry producers in the face of a temporary oversupply of chicken on the local market. This production response appears to have overcompensated, with shortages then emerging and special import arrangements being needed to stabilise the market.</p><p>Since 2000, ‘Guyana has moved from being a net importer of chicken to becoming self-sufficient in poultry meat production’, with poultry meat production having increased from 11,739 tonnes to 27,069 tonnes in 2009 (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Poultry/Guyana-poultry-sector-eying-regional-markets" target="_blank">Guyana poultry sector eying regional markets</a>’, December 2010).</p><p>This expansion has taken place against the backdrop of a 100% tariff, which has been in force since 2003. In addition, import licences are required for poultry product imports from third countries outside CARICOM (for all meat products, not just poultry meat). In the face of this expansion of domestic production, imports have fallen year on year, from 11,362 tonnes in 2000 to only 4–6 tonnes in exceptional years.</p><p>The trade policy applied by Guyana appears to be providing an enabling environment for the poultry industry. However, the essential challenge of securing a reliable supply of competitively priced poultry feed appears to continue to confront the sector, necessitating continued high levels of tariff protection (particularly given the geographical proximity to the world’s leading poultry meat exporter, Brazil).</p><p>Elsewhere in the Caribbean region, there would appear to be some questioning of the appropriateness of high levels of tariff protection in the poultry sector, with discussions taking place in Jamaica over the establishment of a flat-rate 20% import tariff for poultry meat products (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Poultry/Guyana-poultry-sector-eying-regional-markets" target="_blank">Jamaican poultry farmers protest over proposed reduction of import duty</a>’, September 2011). This gives added urgency to addressing the challenge of securing a long-term source of competitively priced poultry feed. In this context, efforts are under way to develop intra-regional supply chains for animal feed, notably between Belize and Jamaica.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
